    {
      "id": "/page/1/Text/9",
      "block_type": "Text",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\">Brownian motion (the \"risk\" part), and a controlled geometric Brownian motion (the investment possibility). Drawdown and shortfall prevention strategies for deterministic liabilities are treated in [6] where it is shown that if the initial wealth or reserve is below the funding level of the perpetual liability, the optimal strategy is linear in the negative surplus, that is, has an <i>inverse</i> CPPI structure, namely <i>k(F</i> − <i>W )</i>. For initial wealth above the funding level, various CPPI strategies using the funding level as the floor are optimal for a variety of utility and probabilistic objectives.</p>",
      "page": 354,
      "polygon": [
        [
          306.84027099609375,
          71.88677978515625
