    {
      "id": "/page/1/Text/10",
      "block_type": "Text",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"Text\">Other settings of interest include cases where there is an exogenous and uncontrollable benchmark relative to which the shortfall is measured. Infinite horizon probabilistic objectives are treated in [8] in an incomplete market setting, and connects these results with those obtained from standard utility maximization problems. A risk-constrained problem that yields a CPPI related strategy is treated in [11]. Stutzer [19] treats long-horizon shortfalls and deviations from benchmarks in the context of a largedeviation approach.</p>",
